`/api/auth/test-token` reads `await c.req.json()` without any error handling or runtime validation. If the request body is invalid JSON or missing fields, Hono will throw and this endpoint will return a 500 instead of a clear 400. Consider wrapping the JSON parse in try/catch and validating `sub/githubId/name` are strings before proceeding (return 400 on invalid input).
```suggestion
    let parsedBody: unknown;
    try {
        parsedBody = await c.req.json();
    } catch {
        return c.json({ error: "Invalid JSON body" }, 400);
    }

    if (
        !parsedBody ||
        typeof parsedBody !== "object" ||
        typeof (parsedBody as any).sub !== "string" ||
        typeof (parsedBody as any).githubId !== "string" ||
        typeof (parsedBody as any).name !== "string"
    ) {
        return c.json({ error: "Invalid request body" }, 400);
    }

    const body = parsedBody as { sub: string; githubId: string; name: string };
```

This endpoint mints a valid JWT for arbitrary user ids when `ENABLE_TEST_AUTH === "true"`. If that flag is ever enabled in a non-test environment (misconfiguration), it becomes a full authentication bypass. To reduce blast radius, consider requiring an additional secret (e.g., `TEST_AUTH_SECRET` header) or restricting by environment/host in addition to the existing flag.
```suggestion
    // Require both a feature flag and a secret header to reduce blast radius
    const enableTestAuth = c.env.ENABLE_TEST_AUTH === "true";
    const testAuthSecret = c.env.TEST_AUTH_SECRET;
    const providedSecret = c.req.header("x-test-auth-secret");

    if (!enableTestAuth || !testAuthSecret || providedSecret !== testAuthSecret) {
        return c.json({ error: "Not Found" }, 404);
    }
```

